segments.text: Camp Williams in San Antonio.
And the trainee of the OTCC that shot the best score in the rifle was given orders to go up to this famous camp up in Illinois.
And they were participating in a national rifle deal.
I won, and the Bullets had the hardest cut, and the next day they were rescinded because we had agreed to let the British Commando Force be coming training there.
That was an outstanding disappointment.
That was an outstanding disappointment.
I never did like the British Commando Forces.
Let's see.
Let's go back to final review.
Your parents came?
Yes.
Any other special people?
My brother and sister-in-law and my sister-in-law.
And that is a special people's organization.
And then describe commencement.
I was very simple.
We did it ahead.
I finally did it ahead.
What's commencement held in Guyon?
Do you remember who the speaker was?
Every name was called.
Every hand shaken.
Let's see, was Reveille around then?
We had the original Reveille.
Describe the original Reveille.
The original Reveille was a curled oak.
It wasn't really a beautiful cottage.
But just like so many other great personalities.
Did Reveille predate your arrival?
Was Reveille on the campus when you arrived as a freshman?
I'm not sure whether he had been in the area or not, but it wouldn't have been more than three or four.
Who took care of Reveille then?
I think one of Porter and the infantry took care of it.
But he won it all.
He literally did?
Yeah.
People always throw the jumps at him for it.
You see, at that time, they had a company called Hamburg Stanton.
Yeah.
Mm-hmm.
Yeah.
It was done from up in the middle of it.
J. Harold Dunn.
Was he a student?
Uh, let's see.
Oh, how good, how good.
Silver Taps.
Where was that held?
Describe it.
And the buglers?
Did it, did the ceremony change as far as you know through the years?
Well, of course, our attendance was almost man-coded.
Everybody was out.
And then we almost have several caps for each individual.
Most of the time you need them.
All right, student diversity.
Were there any Hispanic students?
Did you all identify them in any way different from the others?
Did they have, they didn't?
Were there some Mexican Americans?
Jewish, what about Jewish students?
Did y'all have a special reference title for them?
Were there many international students?
Where were they from primarily?
All right, we got two more questions in.
As you're getting ready to leave with your degree, what kind of world did you think you were entering?
What did you think was ahead of you?
All right, after the Army, what did you think you were going to do?
Well, I had a job at that time.
Did they give you any indication what your pay would be with Humble?
Did they come to the campus to do anything?
Now what was your pay as a second lieutenant?
And you had a three-year obligation or two?
I don't remember.
You had a contract?
Yeah.
About how many remained in the Corps their junior and senior year?
Did everybody?
Well, the people weren't .
All the sophomores are continuing on.
They've been attrition each year.
All right, then the important question.
What did it mean to you, your life, that you went to Texas A&M?
It's probably the most important thing in my life.
Why did you develop this deep love and gratitude for A&M?
But it had a tremendous effect on me.
I was a pretty basic kid.
I mean, I'm probably, although I'm testing on this board, it's going to be still a little aggressive.
A&M gave me an opportunity to develop whatever talents I had to other folks.
And, you know, when you get older, you recommend that.
And you see kids that are following in the same direction, you know.
Somehow or another, even now, the kids who go to A&M seem to get a better direction in their life.
And the students I see going to seminary, they do what they should do.
I'm not alone in sharing the fact that Abraham was very important in the situation of my life.
And then the fellowship and the willingness to help others.
Let's see, that's the important one I forgot.
Do you know anything about the TTs and any other supposed secret fraternities when you were there?
Maybe three or four guys got together and said we could do something with it.
Most of the elections are all hat card elections.
Usually the opportunity is in the infantry, the Calvary, or the campus elections.
Every now and then the Calvary will get together and I'll go for some mission.
What was the most prestigious appointment or a selection or election that an undergraduate could have at A&M then?
Did you, by chance, know Woody Varner?
He's a class ahead of you.
Derwood T. Varner from Cottonwood, Texas.
Let's quit there.
